cs.DS, cs.IR, cs.DB, cs.CC, cs.DC 

The paper deals with data structures for range reporting and prefix reporting, which are classic problems in data structures and algorithms. The use of the I/O model suggests that the paper is likely to be in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. However, the focus on information retrieval applications suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) category. The use of colored sets and the study of three-sided orthogonal range reporting suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.DB (Databases) category. The study of indivisibility assumptions and the exploitation of machine capabilities suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) category. Finally, the consideration of top-k extensions suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) category.
